  "doc_id": "51316",
  "text": "Cadherin function is controlled by proteins associated with the cytoplasmic domain of cadherin, which are collectively called catenins [CITATION_1] . These include et-catenin, [3-catenin, and plakoglobin. Through these proteins, cadherins are thought to interact with the cytoskeleton, and this interaction seems to be essential for the cadherins to exert their full activity. It is now known that 13-catenin directly associates with the cytoplasmic domain of cadherins and that a-catenin binds to this 13-catenin [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] ; i.e., 13-catenin is a mediator for the interaction between cadherin and a-catenin. Two subtypes of et-catenin were identified: one is aE-catenin, expressed mainly by nonneural tissues ; the other, c~N-catenin, is widely expressed by the nervous system [CITATION_4] Uchida et al., 1994, Hirano and . Both subtypes can equally support cadherin function [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] .",
